Lovely spot with much needed shade on a hot day, along with a playground for the children. There is a statue of St.Denis here. Public toilets are available but you will need your own tissues and hand sanitizer.

A picturesque and soul-healing park with two bocce courts, plentiful seating and pretty gardens. A quaint spot to while away the afternoon, removed from the hustle and yahooing of foreign tourists. The toilets were out of order when I was there and hopefully will be repaired soon, and on the presumption they will be, it‚Äôs a five-star touchdown from me.
A small garden with a games area whose name I don't know but it seems to be popular as there were many people playing and watching.
What a great little park to get out and stretch the legs. Just enough for the children to play on, great benches for adult sitting. Plenty of trees to shade during the heat.
It‚Äôs quite and peaceful.

Charming garden with playground, off the beaten path. Public toilets in the stone semi-circular building.

We came here at 1pm and thought there would be a lot of tourists, surprisingly it was almost empty. It‚Äôs quiet in here and relaxing under the trees, a good spot to have a sandwich for lunch. The playground though is for older kids! My 3 year old boy had difficulty with it.
Come here to watch the locals play bacci ball :)

Enough space for kids to run around and play but watch out for a group of old people (neighbors ?) who sometimes complain kids are noisy ! Best to ignor them...( if they need silence, should stay home and fall asleep or consider moving to the countryside...not sit next to kids play area and complain kids are too loud..) Gardners working here are nice people...St.Dennis has his head in his hands...so don't freak out !!
A peaceful bolt hole away from the crowds with a children's play area. Ideal place to rest up between site seeing
Nice, small, cozy Jardin, great atmosphere for family or to Just read a book.
Touristic place. But looks good. Has a lot of shade during summer.
Nice big for Paris park in the middle of the city with a jungle gym for kids.
Lovely, hidden gem of a square, plenty of great gym teachers (including mine).
A very nice and quiet park for kids
loved taking a break here
Quiet little square. Good with young children.
A quiet oasis in Montmarte away from the touristy places.
Peaceful lushly green place. Enjoy. ***

Very successful art deco square. All that is missing is an inscription or plaque to say a little more about the zombie sculpture. In fact we see a bishop carrying his head. It's gory. The fountain reminds us that Saint Denis washed his head there after his beheading.
A well-designed playground for children. And the famous statue of Saint Denis carrying his severed head in his hands, which fascinates all the kids... Nice place.
A wonderful place in the middle of Montmartre. Stopping, drinking water while the children play in the playground, as well as seeing a very beautiful garden, is something surprising.

Lovely quiet square where many locals come. I proposed to my girlfriend here and she said yes! We will definitely come back here to relive the moment. In addition, it is wonderful to escape the hustle and bustle of the city here.
A pretty square in the middle of the 18th century, perfect for relaxing in the sun
Square away from tourist flows where calm reigns... Fresh water fountain and free toilets as a bonus. Thank you to Paris City Hall for maintaining places like this.

Square Suzanne Buisson, with an area of ‚Äã‚Äã2,484 m¬≤, laid out as terraces in 1951 in an art deco style, is located 7bis rue Girardon at the top of Avenue Junot near Place Dalida.  In this discreet location in Montmartre, you can discover a small¬†fountain topped with a statue. A monument a priori quite banal, which nevertheless hides one of the founding myths of Montmartre: that of Saint-Denis, first bishop of Paris, martyr who became legend.  It is said that at this location there was a fountain in which the decapitated Saint washed his head.
Pleasant wooded square with children's play area.

A nice place to stretch out your tired feet. Away from the hustle and bustle, this ‚Äúpark‚Äù is still in the middle of everything. If you've had enough of watching others rub Dalida's breasts for gold, you can relax here. There is a small play area for children, a boules court and a few curiosities. There is actually a prohibition sign on the approximately 12cm deep pool below the statue of Saint Denis that prohibits swimming here. :)
Small garden to rest after the influx of tourists right next door
